    46→/**
    47→ * The Core Unit Dispatcher.
    48→ *
    49→ * The dispatching pipeline is a 3 stage process. Steps 1 and 2 are separate DB transactions.
    50→ *
    51→ * 1. Attempt to start the frame by updating to the Running state. If another thread gets there
    52→ * first, a FrameReservationException is thrown.
    53→ *
    54→ * 2. Reserve processor resources and update resource counts on the host, subscription, job, layer,
    55→ * group, and shot.
    56→ *
    57→ * 3. Contact RQD and launch the frame.
    58→ *
    59→ * Error Handling
    60→ *
    61→ * Depending on where the error happens and what the error is, you might have to take the necessary
    62→ * steps to undo the dispatch because the transaction is not held open the entire time.
    63→ *
    64→ * FrameReservationException - You don't have to undo anything.
    65→ *
    66→ * ResourceDuplicationFailureException - If there is ever a bug that causes the dispatcher to try
    67→ * and dispatch a frame with a proc already assigned to it, catching this and continuing to the next
    68→ * frame will ensure your dispatcher doesn't get stuck trying to launch just one frame. You can also
    69→ * try to fix the frame by running dispatchSupport.fixFrame().
    70→ *
    71→ * ResourceReservationFailureException - This means the host didn't have the resources the
    72→ * dispatcher expected it to have. In this case you have to dispatchSupport.clearFrame(frame) to set
    73→ * the frame back to the Waiting state.
    74→ *
    75→ * For all other exceptions, both the frame and the proc have to be manually removed.
    76→ */
    77→public class CoreUnitDispatcher implements Dispatcher {
    78→    private static final Logger logger = LogManager.getLogger(CoreUnitDispatcher.class);
